{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The attack model is trained through their proposed shadow training technique: First, several \"shadow\" models are constructed to mirror the behavior of the target model, where the training dataset is known, and thus so is the ground truth about the membership.",
    "Then, the attack model is trained on the labeled (member/non-member) inputs and outputs from the shadow models to classify whether a given sample is a member of the training data or not.",
    "Following the formal description of Shokri et al. [239], given an attack target model 𝑓 target (), its private training dataset 𝐷 train target contains labeled training samples (𝑥 𝑖, 𝑦 𝑖) target ∈ 𝐷 train target.",
    "Here, 𝑥 𝑖 target represents the model input, and 𝑦 𝑖 target is the ground truth label, taking a value from a set of 𝑐 target classes.",
    "The target model will output a probability vector 𝑌 𝑖 of size 𝑐 target as the prediction on input 𝑥 𝑖. 𝑓 attack () is the attack model, which is a binary classifier to determine whether a given sample (𝑥, 𝑦) is in the private training dataset (\"in\") or not (\"out\")."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
